OriginalAxioms:
:Vitamin rdfs:comment The vitamin itself not necessarily in the form of
            a pill - could be a constituent of a pill or of food.
            In COSMO this is a Substance, not an Object.
            
            SUMO: A Nutrient present in natural products or made 
            synthetically, which is essential in the diet of Humans and other higher 
            Animals.  Included here are Vitamin precursors and provitamins. 
            
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of vitamin in Wordnet:
              1. 3 vitamin - any of a group of organic substances essential
                in small quantities to normal metabolism

:Inflation rdfs:comment Inflation is the increase or decrease of prices of some set of good and or services,
           measured in some unit of currency over some period of time.
           The EconomicIndicator that measures Inflation is the change of purchasing value of some
           unit of currency, affecting all  agents that use that currency.
             There are several measures of Inflation,
           which are aggregate prices for different sets of goods and/or services.
           The most commonly discussed are the CPI, the consumer price index,
           and the 
          
          Corresponds to part verb noun sense 1 of inflation in WordNet:
             1. 1 inflation, rising prices - a general and progressive increase in prices; 
                in inflation everything gets more valuable except money

:FIBO rdfs:comment A pointer to a corresponding element in the FIBO, an ontology
       of financial eneities being developed by the Object Management Group OMG:
         see http://www.omg.org/spec/EDMC-FIBO/FND/1.0/Beta1/

:CursiveStyleOfWriting rdfs:comment Being in the cursive style of writing for the different
            writing systems

:Translation-Periodic rdfs:comment A specialization of both
            #$Movement-TranslationEvent and #$Movement-Periodic.  Each
            instance of #$Translation-Periodic is a translational
            movement in which the moving object returns to a certain
            location repeatedly, and at more or less regular time
            intervals.  Instances of #$Translation-Periodic include a
            ball bouncing in place and a planet revolving around a star.
            Note that a planet rotating on its axis or a top spinning in
            place would not count as an instance of
            #$Translation-Periodic, since these movements, although
            periodic, are rotations rather than translations.

:CylindricalObject rdfs:comment Each CylindricalObject is a SolidObject
          shaped at least approximately like a Cylinder, whether solid or 
          hollow on the inside;  this may be part of a larger object, and includes 
          Spools on  which cord or sheets can be wound, even though the Spool
          may have flared edges.  A DrinkingMug is Cylindrical
          even though it always has a handle.
          
          NOTE that this is also a StraightObject - if it was curved, it
             would have to be of a different classification -
              if hollow, a tube.
          .

:usesSenseOrOrgan rdfs:comment usesSenseOrOrgan relates a Perceiving or other
       BodilyFunctionEvent to the AnimalBodyPartType or perceptual sense that is used in such
       a Perceiving.  This adds meaning to the Action.

:TimeAgo rdfs:comment A TimeAgo is a TimeInterval or TimePoint whose location in
      time is specified relative to the Now that is contained or implied
      in an assertion.  That happened forty years ago is an example
      of a linguistic expression that uses such a relative time.  In such
      expressions, the word ago serves as a  function to take the
      specified time interval forty years and the implied time Now to return
      a TemporalLocation at which the referenced Event happened..
      
      Corresponds to adjective sense 1 and noun sense 1 of ago in WordNet:
       WN adjective ago:
        1. ago, agone - gone by; or in the past; two years ago; 
            `agone is an archaic word for `ago
       WN adverb ago:
        1. 82 ago - in the past; long ago; sixty years ago my 
            grandfather came to the U.S.

:Mink rdfs:comment 
        
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of mink in Wordnet:
              3. mink - slender-bodied semiaquatic mammal having partially webbed feet; 
                valued for its fur

:DrinkingVessel rdfs:comment Open-top Containers used to hold beverages in a form 
        convenient for consumption.  Beverage bottles are not 
        included, even if many people drink from them, as that is not their
        design purpose.  A baby bottle used with a nipple is also not
        an instance.  A cup or tankard may have a lid, but it is
        used while open-topped, and that determines its place in this
        category.  See e.g. DrinkingCan.
        
        Corresponds to WordNet sense  of drinking vessel:
        1. drinking vessel - a vessel intended for drinking

:Ruminant rdfs:comment A group of mammals which bring previously
            swallowed food back from their stomachs to re-chew into a
            finer and  more digestible consistancy.
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of ruminant in WordNet:
              1. ruminant - any of various cud-chewing hoofed mammals 
                having a stomach divided into four occasionally three compartments

:SecurityRecord rdfs:comment A SecurityRecord is a DatabaseRecord in 
        a DatabaseTable which contains security information
        for the entity whose security information is recorded in the table.
        each such record is pointed to by the relation
        hasSecurityID16 os some parent property or subproperty
        of that relation. The format of the record is
        not restricted by this relation, only its intendede meaning,
        which may vary with the security requirements.

:PhysicalWeb rdfs:comment A physical Network of LongAndThin objects crisscrossing
           to form a mesh pattern.
           
           NOte: WN web has physical object as parent though the gloss example shadows
               is *not* a physical object.
             Corresponds to noun sense 1 of web in WordNet:
                1. 1 web - an intricate network suggesting something that was formed 
                  by weaving or interweaving; the trees cast a delicate web of shadows over the lawn

:Ago rdfs:comment This function can be used with an argument of
        TimeMeasure to return a TimeInterval that is anchored at the
        high end by Now.  See TimeAgo and wasPriorToNowByInterval.

:Humorous rdfs:comment An AttributeValue of an Event or Object or of the
          content of a Communication that causes Amusement or Laughter.
          
          Corresponds to adjective sense 1 of humorous in WordNet:
            1. 9 humorous, humourous - full of or characterized by humor;
               humorous stories; humorous cartoons; in a humorous vein
          .

:TimeMeasure rdfs:comment A measure of a quantity of time, *not* a specific time
    point on the universal time line.
    
    COSMO note: we distinguish TimeMeasures - physical measures that relate to time 
    timeintervals or time points - from the TimePositions - the actual locations in 
    our real time.  The latter are classified under TemporalLocation.  The usage of this
    Type here differs from that in SUMO.  For DateTime see TemporalLocation.

    SUMO:  The class of temporal durations instances of TimeDuration and positions
    of TimePoints and TimeIntervals along the universal timeline instances of TimePosition.

:isTheProfessionOfField rdfs:comment isTheProfessionOfField relates a FieldOfExpertise to some
   Profession usually only one that uses the lore of that FieldOfExpertise 
        to inform its practise.
         
         This relation is useful to fill in the gap between ProfessionalPersons 
         and the FieldOfExpertise in which they are expert.  This gap is partly bridged by the
         requirement for *some* ProfessionalPersons that a ProfessionalPerson is 
         both expert in some field and also practices some Profession.
         .

:IcyCold rdfs:comment IcyCold is a QualitativeAttributeValue for ambient air,
         water, or objects, indicating that the temperature is near or below
         the freezing temperature of water, 0 deg. C down to -20 deg. C. 
         For much colder temperatures, use Cryogenic.
         
         Corresponds to adjective sense 2 of icy in WordNet:
            2. 1 arctic, frigid, gelid, glacial, icy, polar - extremely cold;
               an arctic climate; a frigid day; gelid waters of the North Atlantic;
               glacial winds; icy hands; polar weather

:hasComponentPart rdfs:comment hasComponentPart is a subproperty of hasPhysicalPart
      relating some ArtifactObject to another separately manufactured 
      ArtifactObject which is a part of the larger object.  The
      distinction represented by this relation is that the 
      part must be manufactured separately and assembled into the
      whole object, rather than being some arbitrarily selected
      portion of an ArtifactObject.  An Engine would be a 
      component part of an Automobile; the lower half of a column 
      would not be a component part of the column, though it would
      be a physical part.
      
      NOTe also that the component part may be a Group of things, such
      as a Group of Bristles represented as Bristles in a Brush.

:DesigningEvent rdfs:comment In SUMO and Cyc termed Designing.
        
        SUMO: The spatial analogue of Planning.  Designing a 
         Collection of Objects involves determining a placement of the Objects 
        with respect to one another and perhaps other Objects as well, in order to 
        satisfy a particular purpose.
 
        Cyc:  The act of designing something, be it clothing,
              cars, computer chips or buildings. 
              
           Includes verb senses 2, 3, an 4 and noun sense 1 of design and noun sense 1
                  of designing in WordNet:
              2. 28 design - design something for a specific role or purpose or effect;
                  This room is not designed for work
	      3. 19 design - create the design for; create or execute in an artistic
	           or highly skilled manner; Chanel designed the famous suit
              4. 8 design, plan - make a design of; plan out in systematic, often graphic form; 
                  design a better mousetrap; plan the new wing of the museum
            WN nou design
                1. 13 design, designing - the act of working out 
                  the form of something as by making a sketch or outline or plan; 
                  he contributed to the design of a new instrument

:WildAnimal rdfs:comment A specialization of #$NonPersonAnimal. Each
            instance of this collection is a non-human animal that is
            not domesticated or tame.  Note that a captive animal may
            still be a wild animal, e.g. zoo animals that are not tame
            or domesticated.  Specializations of #$WildAnimal are
            returned by #$WildAnimalFn. See also #$CaptiveAnimal, #$DomesticatedAnimal.

:AttributeType rdfs:comment An AttributeType is a general category of attribute, i.e.
    some property that adheres in an object, such as length or mass or 
    color or shape for physical objects.  More abstract objects such as 
    sets or groups may have more abstract attributes such as cardinality.
    The distinction between attributes and relations between entities is not 
    absolute.
    
    COSMO note:  The use of two distinct trees of attribute-related types
    AttributeType and AttributeValue is intended to enable assertions with
    a linguistic form such as:
          {Jack has Height {6 feet}
     where the second argument Height specifies the general type of attribute,
     and the value {6 feet} specifies the specific attribute value, where
     feet is a function returning a distance measure.  This generic attribute
     assertion can then be used with other types of attributes, such as:
          {Jack has Weight {60 kilograms} and
          {Car037 has Color RedColor.
          
     Corresponds to noun sense 1 of attribute and sense 3 and 4 of
       property in WordNet:
       1. 2 property, attribute, dimension - a construct whereby objects
           or individuals can be distinguished; self-confidence is
           not an endearing property
       WN noun Property:
        3. 138 property - a basic or essential attribute shared by 
            all members of a class; a study of the physical properties of atomic particles
        4. 32 property, attribute, dimension - a construct whereby 
            objects or individuals can be distinguished;
            self-confidence is not an endearing property

:Jaded rdfs:comment The attribute of someone experiencing BeingTiredOfSomething.
          This attribute means more than just the dulled in WordNet,
          it includes a positive preference not to see any more of the same
          thing.
        
        Corresponds approximately to adjective sense 2 of jaded in WordNet:
          2. 2 jaded - dulled by surfeit; the amoral, jaded,
            bored upper classes

:Generation rdfs:comment Each Generation is a GroupOfAnimals that have a common number of 
       ancestors in the line to a common ancestor.

      @ToDO: how to express that??
      
           Corresponds to noun sense 2 of generation in WordNet:
             2. 7 generation - group of genetically related organisms constituting
               a single step in the line of descent

:Prickly rdfs:comment The property of SolidObjects that
          have multiple barbs or spikes e.g. Prickles sticking out from their
          surface, like a Cactus or a burr or prickly pear cactus fruit,
          or a porcupine.  The barb does not have to be a PlantPart.
          To be Prickly means to have multiple pointy-ended spikes sticking out from 
          the main body of the object - but NOTE: this is a @default@ property, which is 
          expected to be true of typical objects having this AttributeValue; any given instance can be shorn
          of its spikes or thorns and still be an instance of the type.
          An object that is Prickly is not necessarily barbed at every
          region on it surface.
          
          Corresponds to adjective sense 2 of prickly in WordNet:
            2. barbed, barbellate, briary, briery, bristled, bristly,
                burred, burry, prickly, setose, setaceous, spiny, thorny -
                having or covered with protective barbs or quills or spines 
                or thorns or setae etc.; a horse with a short bristly mane; 
                bristly shrubs; burred fruits; setaceous whiskers

:NotUnreasonable rdfs:comment NotUnreasonable is an AttributeValue modifying actions or policies,
       and is not applied to people use Reasonable or quantitative measures use NotExcessive.
       Use of NotUnreasonable indicates that the action or policy modified
       is of a type that a Reasonable person would make, showing sound judgment.
       Applying this attribute is to make a judgment based on normal behaviors
       or policies .  Example: drive at a reasonable speed;
       drinking a reasonable amount of alcohol wont get you drunk.
      
      Includes adjective sense 3 and part of sense 1 of reasonable the part
         not applying directly to people in WordNet:
         1. 17 reasonable, sensible - showing reason or sound judgment; a sensible choice; 
            a sensible person
         3. reasonable, sane -- marked by sound judgment; sane nuclear policy

:ContainerByVolume rdfs:comment A ContainerByVolume is a ContainerArtifact that
          has a specified volume.  This type allows one to specify, e.g. 
          a gallon jug or quart container.  The volume must be specified.

:VoltageSource rdfs:comment A source of electrical voltage.
        
        COSMO note: This category is interpreted as 
        being a physical object that has connecting terminals 
        that connect to some form of power supply.
        It may merely be a connector, such as  a
        WallOutlet, or may be the power generator itself,
        such as a Battery.  The criterion is to have
        terminals to which electrical devices can be 
        connected.  This device must have two terminals - for certain
        power lines that depend on a ground, the ground terminal
        is connected to the physical ground.
        
        NOTE also that in Cyc there is a 
        distinction between VoltageSource and
        CurrentSource.  Apparently, a
        CurrentSource is suppopsed to be the unit that actually
        generates the power, but Cyc has PowerSupply as
        a subtype, and the PowerSupply in typical devices
        does not generate power, rather it converts
        line power to another voltage.  In COSMO
        CurrentSource is renamed as PowerGenerator

:Barber rdfs:comment A person who cuts the HeadHair or facial hair of clients to make 
               their appearance more pleasing to someone.
            
               Corresponds to noun sense 1 of barber in Wordnet:
                  2. barber - a hairdresser who cuts hair and shaves beards as a trade

:BackwardMotion rdfs:comment A Translocation that is in the direction pointed to
        by the front-to-back vector of a FrontAndBacksidedObject.
        In some cases this can be termed going backwars.

:isPartlySupportedBy rdfs:comment This is contrued somewhat differentyl from in CYC -  one leg of a chair or 
          a pier of a bridge would use the subproperty supports even if it provides
          only part of the total support.  This relation includes supporting such as 
          that provided by the back of a chair or  brace or splint on a body part.
       
            From Cyc supportedBy-Contributing:
            A isParlySupportedBy B means that B provides *at least*
            some of the support required to maintain A from falling in a gravitational
            field.  B may actually provide all of the support, and
            isSupportedBy is a subproperty of this property.
            The supporting object must actually touch the object
            being supported.  There is no relation of indirect partial support
            yet in COSMO, which would be a transitive relation, as of v0.55.
            This is used for cases where, e.g. each leg of a table partly
            supports the table top.
            
            Cyc: A generalization of #$supportedBy.
            #$supportedBy-Contributing OBJECT SUPPORT means that
            SUPPORT contributes  to the total amount of support holding
            OBJECT up and maintaining its vertical position.  If SUPPORT
            were to be removed, then everything else being equal
            OBJECT would have less support against falling down than
            before. OBJECT might even actually fall, but not
            necessarily.  For example, a bridge is
            #$supportedBy-Contributing each individual pile underneath
            it, though it is unlikely to be crucially #$supportedBy any
            one of them.

:Leather rdfs:comment The Substance Leather - for a piece of Leather,
           use LeatherObject.  Note that as a subtype of Fabric,
           Leather is considered an ArtificialSubstance - because
           it must be processed to become Leather.
          
        Cyc: A specialization of #$SolidTangibleThing. Each
            instance of #$Leather is a piece of tanned animal hide.
            Instances of #$Leather are commonly used as material inputs
            to the manufacture of shoes, gloves, upholstery, satchels
            and purses, saddles, and other items.
            
            SUMO: A Fabric that is the result of tanning an Animal 
             Skin.
             
             Corresponds to noun sense 1 of leather in WordNet:
              1. 11 leather - an animal skin made smooth and flexible by removing
               the hair and then tanning

:Racket rdfs:comment A  prolonged series of  Noises that may be distracting or annoying.
     
              Corresponds to noun sense 1 of noise in WordNet:
                   1. 3 racket - a loud and disturbing noise

:Italy rdfs:comment 
                   Corresponds to noun sense 1 of Italy in WordNet:
                     1. 6 Italy, Italian Republic, Italia - a republic in southern Europe
                      on the Italian Peninsula; was the core of the Roman Republic
                      and the Roman Empire between the 4th century BC and the 5th century AD

:ProfessionalPerson rdfs:comment A person with a skill at some activity that can 
           be paid for.  COSMO note: this type and its subtypes do not
          require that a person characterized by one of these types
          necessarily makes a living from performing the skills
          associated with these type.  This type is a designation for
          skilled people, and skilled people who are amateurs or volunteers
          also qualify, but the skill must be at the level of a
          professional, and the activity must be one that people 
          are commonly paid for performing, when working for the benefit of
          others.

            COSMO note: in COSMO there is a borderline set of occupations that
              can be considered as trades and also as professional,
              such as Butcher and Baker.
          
          If one wants to specify only adults that are professionals, one can use Professional-Adult.
        
          Cyc: The collection of all people who work at a job that
            requires a skill that most adults do not have.  This skill is
            normally achieved through training, however people who use a
            native  skill such as an artistic skill, in their work are
            also considered Professionals.  A person with a
            #$HighSchoolDiploma, but no additional training, is not
            expected to be able to be hired to a professional position
            and perform the job requirements.  The training need not be
            academic in nature.  One can be a professional child
            actress, chess player, boxer, or shaman, as well as a
            professional lawyer, architect, secretary, or politician.
            Although factory workers, farm workers, construction
            workers, etc. develop a level of skill that makes them able
            to do their jobs far better than a person off the street
            professional or not these positions are not considered
            professional positions because the skill is developed
            experientially on the job.
            NOTE that this includes two distinguishable senses of 
            professional 1 a member of one of the learned professions -
            doctor, lawyer, teacher, scientist;
            2 someone who does something for pay.  WordNet sense 2 is
            a specialization of this second sense, for athletes.  But one
            can also be a professional dancer or professional gambler.
            See adjective Professional.
             
            
            Includes noun senses 1 and 2 of professional in WordNet:
              1. 3 professional, professional person - a person engaged in one of
                   the learned professions
              2. 1 professional, pro - an athlete who plays for pay

:Perceptible rdfs:comment Perceptible is an AttributeValue things PhysicalObjects, 
       Events,  or of more subtle AttributeValues that can be
       perceived by human senses *and* require some degree of inference or understanding,
       i.e. include the use of the mind not only the senses.
           e.g. requiring use of the memory: perceptible changes in behavior
              requiring understanding of the meaning:  an obvious or palpable lie
              requiring understanding of behavior: a detectable note of sarcasm
              requiring understanding of speech patterns and timing:
                                       he continued after a perceptible pause  
                                       after a noticeable pause the lecturer continued
        
        The subtype Obvious is more specific in meaning easy to understand, rather than
            easy to erceive with the senses.
        
        Corresponds to parts noun senses 1, 2, and 3 of perceptible that refer to 
           perceiving with the human senses, and sense 1 of palpable and sense 2 of noticeable 
             and adjective sense 1 of obvious in Wordnet:
         WN adjective perceptible:
           1. 1 perceptible - capable of being perceived by the mind or senses; a perceptible limp;
              easily perceptible sounds; perceptible changes in behavior
	   2. perceptible - easily perceived by the senses or grasped by the mind;
	     a perceptible sense of expectation in the court; an obvious or palpable lie
           3. detectable, perceptible - easily seen or detected; a detectable note of sarcasm;
         WN adjective detectable:
           1. 7 detectable, noticeable - capable of being detected;
                after a noticeable pause the lecturer continued
             he continued after a perceptible pause
         WN adjective palpable:
           1. 1 palpable, tangible - capable of being perceived by the senses or the mind;
              especially capable of being handled or touched or felt; a barely palpable dust; 
              felt sudden anger in a palpable wave; the air was warm and close - palpable as cotton
         WN adjective noticeable:
           2. 1 detectable, noticeable - capable of being detected; 
                after a noticeable pause the lecturer continued
         WN adjective obvious:
           1. 27 obvious - easily perceived by the senses or grasped by the mind; obvious errors

:Admiration rdfs:comment A pleasant emotional state caused by
          observing or becoming aware of something of which one
          strongly approves - either because of its intrinsic positive qualities, 
          or because as a persons action it signifies some state
          of which one approves.  Admiration can be directed toward
          natural things to admire the view, or toward supernatural beings,
          but is usually toward people see the subtype Admiration-Respect or 
          things done by or made by people.

          A Liking in which the object of liking is another
            person, and the cause of the Admiring is an approval of some of the 
            admired persons actions, plus an evaluative feeling tha tthiose actions
            are worthy of copying or mimicing.          
            This sense is broader than the Cyc sense, which is 
            specifically for admiration of people.   For the Cyc sense,
            see Admiration-Respect.
          
          Corresponds to noun sense 1 of admiration and verb sense 1 of
            admire in WordNet:
            1. 8 admiration, esteem - a feeling of delighted approval and liking
           WN verb admire:
             1. 13 admire, look up to - feel admiration for

:wasAffectedByAction rdfs:comment The inverse of hadAffectedAgent - relates
                 an agent or agents to some action by which s/he
                 was affected.

:Antenna-AnimalBodyPart rdfs:comment CYC: A movable segmented organ of sensation located on
            the head of insects, crustaceans and arachnids.
            
              Corresponds to noun sense 3 of antenna in WordNet:
                3. antenna, feeler - one of a pair of mobile appendages on the head of e.g. insects and crustaceans; typically sensitive to touch and taste

:Execution-Judicial rdfs:comment A specialization of #$KillingFn #$HomoSapiens
            and #$Punishing. Each element of #$Execution-Judicial is a
            judicially sanctioned action of putting a person to death as
            a punishment for some crime. Thus, it excludes Mafia
            hits and euthanasia, even if the euthanasia is
            sanctioned by some part of the judicial system.

:Orderliness rdfs:comment A PersistentState in which objects are arranged
      in a manner conforming to a rule, or people act
      according to explicit or implicit societal rules.
      
      This corresonds to noun sense 2 of orderliness and refers to
        noun senses 3, 4, and and 5 of order in WordNet:
     WN noun orderliness:
        2. orderliness, order - a condition of regular or proper arrangement;
        he put his desk in order; the machine is now in working order
     WN noun order:
      3. 7 order - established customary state especially of society;
         order ruled in the streets; law and order
      4. 7 ordering, order, ordination - logical or comprehensible 
         arrangement of separate elements; we shall consider these 
         questions in the inverse order of their presentation
      5. 4 orderliness, order - a condition of regular or proper 
          arrangement; he put his desk in order; 
          the machine is now in working order

:ManualLaborer rdfs:comment 
           Corresponds to noun sense 1 of manual laborer in WordNet:
             1. laborer, manual laborer, labourer, jack -
             someone who works with their hands; someone engaged in manual labor

:EvaluativeAttribute rdfs:comment An EvaluativeAttribute is a  QualitativeAttributeValue
      for some entity, concrete or abstract, that reflects the judgment 
      of an IntelligentAgent regarding that entity.  the judgment may be
      objective or subjective, but will be relative to some purpose.
      
      @ToDo: in assigning an EvaluativeAttribute, it should be
      necessary to specify the agent who has assigned that attribute value -
      but at this point rev833 there is no mechanism for specifying
      the agent directly, other than in a reified assertion.

:Honestly rdfs:comment Honestly is an AdverbialModifier that modifies an Assertion,
            indicating the the speaker is being truthful.  
            
             Corresponds to adverb sense 1 of honestly in WordNet:
               1. 6 honestly, candidly, frankly - used as intensives reflecting the speakers attitude
                 it is sincerely the case that; honestly, I dont believe it; 
                 candidly, I think she doesnt have a conscience; frankly, my dear, I dont give a damn

:Bookcase rdfs:comment A Bookcase is a piece of furniture that has at least two shelves,
          used for holding books.
            
            Corresponds to noun sense 1 of bookcase in Wordnet:
               1. 2 bookcase - a piece of furniture with shelves for storing books

:InsuranceContent rdfs:comment Each InsuranceContent is a Promise a LinguisticAssertion,
          a phrase in some human language - not the Proposition represented
          by the phrase that describes the Event insured against, the
          reimbursement amount and type, and other conditions.  This will
          refer to an EventType which is the type of Event insured against.
          
          Corresponds approximately to noun sense 1 of insurance in WordNet:
            1. 7 insurance - promise of reimbursement in the case of loss;
               paid to people or companies so concerned about hazards that they
               have made prepayments to an insurance company
          .

:GlassFul rdfs:comment A GlassFul is the quantity that will fill a 
       container called a Glass, not much different from a Cupful.
    
        Corresponds to noun sense 3 of glass in WordNet:
           3. 7 glass, glassful - the quantity a glass will hold

:OdorAttribute rdfs:comment Each OdorAttribute is a QualitativeAttributeValue that characterizes
            the Odor of a substance, object, or location.

:DifficultToUnderstand rdfs:comment An attribute of texts, Assertions, or propositions which 
           are not easy to undeerstand.  .This is an EvaluativeAttribute
           because texts that are incomprehensible to some people may
           be easy for others to understand.
           
           Includes part of  adjective sense 1 of mysterious in WordNet, but does
            not include the sense of the inscrutable 
               workings of Providence which is represented by Mysterious; also
               includes both senses 1 and 2 of incomprehensible in WN sense 1 is
               a deeper level of incomprehensibility than sense 2; and includes
               sense 1 of cryptic in WN
            WN mysterious
            1. 14 cryptic, cryptical, deep, inscrutable, mysterious, mystifying -
               of an obscure nature; the new insurance policy is written without
               cryptic or mysterious terms; a deep dark secret; the inscrutable 
               workings of Providence; in its mysterious past it encompasses all 
               the dim origins of life- Rachel Carson; rituals totally mystifying 
               to visitors from other lands
            WN incomprehensible:
              1. 1 inexplicable, incomprehensible - incapable of being explained 
                 or accounted for; inexplicable errors; left the house at three 
                 in the morning for inexplicable reasons
              2. 1 incomprehensible, uncomprehensible - difficult to understand; 
                  the most incomprehensible thing about the universe is that it 
                  is comprehensible- A. Einstein
             WN cryptic
               1. 2 cryptic, cryptical, deep, inscrutable, mysterious, mystifying -
                  of an obscure nature; the new insurance policy is written without
                  cryptic or mysterious terms; a deep dark secret; the inscrutable
                  workings of Providence; in its mysterious past it encompasses
                  all the dim origins of life- Rachel Carson; rituals totally mystifying
                  to visitors from other lands

:Raw rdfs:comment An Attribute of Food uncooked.
        
        Cyc: An instance of #$PreparationAttribute. Instances
            of #$Raw are in or nearly in their natural state, and in
            particular have not been #$Cooked.
            
            @ToDo: Metaphorical uses such as rawdata are not yet rev1067 represented.

:VocalCords rdfs:comment The type VocalCords is grammatically plural, but here is interpreted

:Sugar-Generic rdfs:comment A substance consisting of carbohydrates with no

         Corresponds to noun sense 1 of tadpole in WordNet:
           1. 1 tadpole, polliwog, pollywog - a larval frog or toad

:Ant rdfs:comment Corresponds to noun sense 1 of ant in WordNet:
          1. 6 ant, emmet, pismire - social insect living in organized colonies;

:for rdfs:comment The preposition for has multiple linguistic senses
      33 of them in RHW.  These are not enumerated here, and will need to

      those concepts..

:Weasel rdfs:comment 
          Corresponds to noun sense 1 of weasel in Wordnet:
             1. weasel - small carnivorous mammal with short legs and elongated body and neck

:FeelingAttribute rdfs:comment Each FeelingAttribute is the attribute of someone 
      who is experiencing a specific Feeling.  For example, afraid
      is the attribute of someone feeling Fear; Courageous is
      the attribute of someone feeling Courage.
      
      
       NOTE that a subtype of BehaviorAttribute can also be a subtype of FeelingAttribute;
              e.g. Bold can be a Feeling one can feel bold, or it can be a behavior attribute
              that inlines one to bold actions.  There may be a distinction, but that has not been 
              formalized as of rev 1195.

:Afrikaans rdfs:comment 
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of Afrikaans in WordNet:
          1. Afrikaans, Taal, South African Dutch - an official language of the Republic of South Africa;

        .

:SecondFn rdfs:comment A BinaryFunction that assigns a PositiveRealNumber and a subclass of Minutes to the Seconds
    within each Minute corresponding to that PositiveRealNumber.  For example, SecondFn 4 MinuteFn 5 Hour
    is the Class of all fourth Seconds of every fifth Minute of every hour.
    For another example, SecondFn 8 Minute would return the eighth second of every minute.  
    For still another example, SecondFn 9 MinuteFn 15 HourFn 14 DayFn 18 MonthFn 8 YearFn 1912 
    denotes 9 seconds and 15 minutes after 2 PM on the 18th day of August 1912.

:pounds rdfs:comment Corresponds to noun sense 1 of pound in WordNet:
         1. 46 pound, lb - 16 ounces; he got a hernia when he tried to lift 100 pounds

:Smiling rdfs:comment Only primates smile.  Requires lips.  Also may
            involve the whole face and perhaps mouth.   Should that be
            inferable from the fact use of lips involves face and mouth? 
            
            SUMO: Spreading the lips in such a way as to convey 
              happiness.
              
            Corresponds to verb sense 1 of smile in WordNet:
              1. 79 smile - - change ones facial expression by spreading 
              the lips, often to signal pleasure

:Can rdfs:comment In COSMO a Can  is necessarily metallic.
        It may be reclosable, such as the cans used for paint,
        or single-use, such as the cans one opens with a can opener
        that cannot be reclosed with the same lid.
        Cyc restricts this to Food, but in COSMO it can be any 
        can-shaped metallic container, including cans for paint,
        driveway sealer, etc.
        
        Cyc: Cylindrical storage device often used to store food.
        
        Corresponds to noun sense 1 of can in WordNet:
          1. 3 can, tin, tin can - airtight sealed metal
             container for food or drink or paint etc.

:Pipe rdfs:comment In Cyc called Pipe-ConduitArtifact.
        COSMO:  Any kind of pipe-like  artifact - plastic, glass, steel,
        rubber, flexible or rigid.  Laboratory glass tubing and
        garden hose both qualify as a pipe.
    
     Cyc:  The collection of all manufactured enclosed
            tubular fluid conduits with openings at both ends.  The more
            general #$Pipe-GenericConduit encompasses both such
            manufactured pipes and natural pipes which are not instances
            of #$Pipe-ConduitArtifact, i.e. those found naturally
            occurring in the environment or in an organisms body,
            such as #$BloodVessels.
            
           Corresponds to noun sense 2 of pipe in WordNet but may
             also be composed of glass or ceramic like clay:
             2. 4 pipe, pipage, piping - a long tube made of metal or
               plastic that is used to carry water or oil or gas etc.

:GlobalWarmingEvent rdfs:comment COSMO note: an Event - the global warming
        during any given interval of Time.
        
        Cyc: Collection of global warming events.  A global
            warming event is a general warming of the average
            temperature of the Earth.

:Sulfur rdfs:comment An essential component of proteins, each atom has 16 protons in the 
        nucleus.  The powdered form is usually yellow in color.
        
          Corresponds to noun sense 1 of sulfur in Wordnet:
             1. 6 sulfur, S, sulphur, atomic number 16 - an abundant tasteless odorless
                multivalent nonmetallic element; best known in yellow crystals; occurs in many sulphide
                and sulphate minerals and even in native form especially in volcanic regions

:FunnyEvent rdfs:comment A FunnyEvent is an Event that causes an IntelligentAgent
          to experience Mirth.  The Event causing Mirth does
          not necessarily have to be an action of a cognitive agent, because
          amusement can occur due to naturally occurring events involving
          inanimate objects.
          
          The restriction causes Laughing means that it *often* causes
            Laughing, though not always.
:BodyJoint rdfs:comment The SUMO equivalent of Joint-AnimalBodyPart.

:Competitive rdfs:comment Competitive is an AttributeValue of an animal that is 
    more than average incliued to compete rather than cooperate
    with others, or enjoys competition.  , i.e. .  This attribute may apply
      only for a short time or in a specific situation, as during a competition.
      However, it may also be used to characterize an animals or persons
      habitual mode of behavior in some types of situation.
      This applies to sports, commercial transactions, or other forms 
      of interaction.
      
      This corresponds to adjective sense 3 of fierce in WordNet:
        3. 1 competitive, militant - showing a fighting disposition; 
          highly competitive sales representative; militant in fighting for 
          better wages for workers; his self-assertive and ubiquitous energy

:isWearing rdfs:comment isWearing relates an agent, which could
          be an animal or an inanimate thing like a mannequin,
          to some instance of SomethingToWear that the
          agent is wearing at some particular time.
          NO distinction is made between sense 1 and 2 of wear in WordNet because
          is can be difficult to decide whether someone is dressed in some
          item or merely bears it on ones person; someone wearing a gold
          wristwatch or Jewelrey is an instance of this relation.
          
          See also WearingSomething for the closely related Action.
        
          Includes verb sense 1 and 2 of wear in WordNet:
            1. 85 wear, have on - be dressed in; She was wearing yellow that day
            2. 22 wear, bear - have on ones person; He wore a red ribbon;
                bear a scar

:Hot rdfs:comment Hot is a QualitativeAttributeValue for objects,
           indicating that the temperature of the object is significantly
           above a persons body temperature.  For air,hot
           starts at about 85 deg F.  For solid objects, a temperature
           of over 45 or 50 deg C would start to be uncomfortable for a person to handle,
           and be considered hot.
           
           Corresponds to sense 1 of hot in WordNet:
             1. 58 hot - used of physical heat; having a high or higher than desirable 
                temperature or giving off heat or feeling or causing a sensation of heat 
                or burning; hot stove; hot water; a hot August day; a hot stuffy room;
                shes hot and tired; a hot forehead

:HailStone rdfs:comment A specialization of #$PrecipitationParticle.
            Instances of #$HailStone are small particles emitted from
            clouds in instances of #$HailProcess q.v..  Instances of
            #$HailStone usually consist of several concentric layers of ice.
            
              Corresponds to noun sense 1 of hailstone in Wordnet:
                 1. hailstone - small pellet of ice that falls during a hailstorm

:Popularity rdfs:comment  Popularity is a subtype of PopularityRating which
        includes those values showing that some thing is Popular, i.e. having
        more favorable opinions than unfavorable.  To have Popularity is to 
        be Popular.
          
        Corresponds approximately to part of noun sense 1 of popularity in WordNet;
          the WordNet gloss indicates that this term is used mostly for 
          highly favorable PropularityRatings, but this COSMO type is
          for any positive favorable rating.
                1. 6 popularity -
                the quality of being widely admired or accepted or sought after;
                his charm soon won him affection and popularity;
                the universal popularity of American movies

:Compass rdfs:comment A device used to find directions, especially one
            which uses a magnet to point to magnetic north a
            #$MagneticCompass, or a gyroscope to point to true north a #$GyroCompass.
            
            SUMO: A Device that indicates the direction of North.
            
              Corresponds to noun sense 1 of compass in Wordnet:
                 1. 3 compass - navigational instrument for finding directions

:Solder rdfs:comment A bonding material consisting of an Alloy
          used to make connections between two metal objects, such as between parts of an
          electronic circuit, or in jewelry.

           Solder is used to make a Connection-Physical and in so doing,
             it forms part of the connection.
             
             @ToDo: define soldering?

              Corresponds to noun sense 1 of solder in WordNet:
                1. 1 solder - an alloy usually of lead and tin used when melted 
                  to join two metal surfaces

:UnilateralGetting rdfs:comment Any instance of Getting that is not part 
          of a Transaction.  In other words, any instance of Getting where nothing 
          is given in return.  Some examples of UnilateralGetting are:  appropriating, 
           commandeering, stealing, etc..

:Convenient rdfs:comment This includes three subsenses: Appropriate to the occasion because it
      is either 1 easy to do actions -  use EasyToDo or 2 or easy to use 
        objects or places.  Something may be easy to use simply because it is nearby : e,g,
         a convenient grocery store; 3 nearby is a subsense of 2.
        same as a conveniently located grocery store.
        See also the somewhat related Practical: some things may be
        Practical because they use Convenient resources - but @ToDo the
        relation between Practical and concenient has not been formalized
        as of rev817.
      
       There are two senses of convenient in RHW:
       1. suitable or agreeable to the needs or purpose; well-suited with 
          respect to facility or ease in use; favorable, easy, or comfortable for use.
       2. at hand; easily accessible: 
          Their house is convenient to all transportation.
          
       There are two non-archaic senses of convenient in WordNet:
       1. 18 convenient - suited to your comfort or purpose or needs;
          a convenient excuse for not going
       2. 3 convenient, handy, ready to hand - easy to reach;
           found a handy spot for the can opener
       3. commodious, convenient - large and roomy convenient is archaic in this sense;
          a commodious harbor; a commodious building suitable for conventions

:RareEvent rdfs:comment A RareEvent is an Event that seldom occurs, sufficiently unusual to be noteworthy.
            
            Corresonds to part of sense 1 of oddity in RHW the event part:
              1. an odd or remarkably unusual person, thing, or event.  A truly odd event might
                be called a wonder.

              that Events are included amnong oddities, though not mentioned in the WN
              documentation.:
              1. 2 curio, curiosity, oddity, oddment, peculiarity, rarity -
                something unusual - perhaps worthy of collecting

               1. 2 brake - a restraint used to slow or stop a vehicle

:Attendee rdfs:comment An Attendee is the Role of a Person who is present at some Event,
           usually but not necessarily a meeting.

             1. attendant, attender, attendee, meeter - a person who is present and participates in a meeting;
               he was a regular attender at department meetings; the gathering satisfied both organizers and attendees

:NonCurrent rdfs:comment NonCurrent  is the attribute of things - objects, practices,
        events - that are no longer ocurring or are out-of-date.

            WN out-of-date
              1. obsolete, outdated, out-of-date, superannuated - old; no longer in use

               outdated equipment; superannuated laws; out-of-date ideas

:isNearTo rdfs:comment isNearTo specifies that some GenericLocation an
      Object or a Region is near to another, but usually not touching the
      other.  near is relative to the size of the things being related.  
      To be near another region or object, the distance from one Object or
      Region to the other must be within two diameters of the larger object or region.
      NOTE that isSupportedBy is a subproperty of isNearTo.
      
      Is this really symmetric for objects of greatly different sizes?
    
       See also the QualitativeAttributeValue Near and Far, which may be used
       in linguistic expressions to express this concept.  @ToDo - relate the
       attributes to this relation??
    
      If two objects are touching, that can be represented as a TouchingState.
    
      In SUMO treated as an attribute:
      SUMO: Near The relation of common sense adjacency.  Note that, if 
       an object is Near another object, then the objects are not connected..

:Recording rdfs:comment A Recording is a PhysicalObject created by a
       InformationRecordingDevice, that contains a representation
       of some Record which is an abstract sequence of symbols
       representing the sequence of changes in an Event.
       NOTE that an InformationRecordingDevice is an artifact, therefore
       the brain, which  can record information is not an instance,
       and the information in the brain is not a Recording.
       A hand transcription of speech is not a Recording.
       NOTE: one may distinguish an original recording from an
       InformationRecordingDevice from copies of that original recording,but
       at this point rev827 COSMO does not make that distinction.  Therefore every 
       copy of a phonograph record, audio tape, photographic image,
       whether original or reproduced by some accurate reproduction
       process, is an instance of this type.
       
       For the act of recording something use InformationRecordingEvent.
       
       @ToDo: NOTE that the restriction isCreatedByDeviceType InformationRecordingDevice,
          if applicable to copies, would imply that a copying device is an InformationRecordingDevice.
          This is not quite the intended meaning though it is not unreasonable,
          and copies may need to be represented separately from originals.
       
       Corresponds to part of noun sense 1 of record in WordNet
       the part that is a record created by a device, not by hand:
          1. 238 record - anything such as a document or a phonograph record 
             or a photograph providing permanent evidence of or information about past events;
             the film provided a valuable record of stage techniques

:InternalState rdfs:comment Each InternalState is a PersistentState in which some set of
      component parts of a System maintain a stable configuration the properties 
      of the components and relations among them are constant within the limits
      considered significant for some interval of time.  The system can
      be a living organism or part of an organism, or some artifact that
      is designed to have alternative internal states such as a thermostat.
      
      Feelings of cognitive agents are example of InternalState.

:Bottle rdfs:comment A cylindrical container for holding stuff, usually always? a
            liquid, with a single portal at the end of a Constriction
            on the very top.  The difference between  a Jar and a Bottle 
            in COSMO is only in the width of the opening, relative to the width of the container.
            For COSMO purposes, a Jar has an opening diameter at least half the 
            maximum diameter of the cylindrical portion, and a Bottle has an opening
            diameter less than half the maximum diameter.  SUMO requires that a
            Bottle have no handle, but that is not a requirement in COSMO.  The small
            handles on some bottles do not disqualify them.
            
            The part BottleNeck provides more detail about the characteristic features
               of a Bottle.
                           
            @ToDo: there may be some use having a subtype with handles, perhaps called jug.
            
            SUMO: A Container whose top is narrower than its bottom, which 
            has no handle, and which is intended to store Liquids.

            1. 32 bottle - a glass or plastic vessel used for storing 
               drinks or other liquids; typically cylindrical without handles
               and with a narrow neck that can be plugged or capped

:hasRepresentation rdfs:comment hasRepresentation is the most general relation that points from some
    concept or thing - of any type - to another thing abstract or physical that
    represents it in some way.  The representation that is pointed to may be abstract or
    physical.  This relation will be used, if at all, less frequently than the more specific
   representation relations e.g. hasAbstractRepresentation and hasPhysicalRepresentation,
    and may be useful primarily to collect those more specific relations
    in one location to make the representation relations easier to understand.
    
    The related relation hasURL points to a datatype string that is the address
    of some file relevant to the subject entity.  As a datatype relation,

                express indirectly by an image, form, or model; be a symbol;

    For still another example, SecondFn 9 MinuteFn 15 HourFn 14 DayFn 18 MonthFn 8 YearFn 1912 
    denotes 9 seconds and 15 minutes after 2 PM on the 18th day of August 1912.

f045bf4b-7e3e-473d-9dd3-17b441c5a86f rdf:type A Recording is a PhysicalObject created by a
       InformationRecordingDevice, that contains a representation
       of some Record which is an abstract sequence of symbols
       representing the sequence of changes in an Event.
       NOTE that an InformationRecordingDevice is an artifact, therefore
       the brain, which  can record information is not an instance,
       and the information in the brain is not a Recording.
       A hand transcription of speech is not a Recording.
       NOTE: one may distinguish an original recording from an
       InformationRecordingDevice from copies of that original recording,but
       at this point rev827 COSMO does not make that distinction.  Therefore every 
       copy of a phonograph record, audio tape, photographic image,
       whether original or reproduced by some accurate reproduction
       process, is an instance of this type.
       
       For the act of recording something use InformationRecordingEvent.
       
       @ToDo: NOTE that the restriction isCreatedByDeviceType InformationRecordingDevice,
          if applicable to copies, would imply that a copying device is an InformationRecordingDevice.
          This is not quite the intended meaning though it is not unreasonable,
          and copies may need to be represented separately from originals.
       
       Corresponds to part of noun sense 1 of record in WordNet
       the part that is a record created by a device, not by hand:
          1. 238 record - anything such as a document or a phonograph record 
             or a photograph providing permanent evidence of or information about past events;
             the film provided a valuable record of stage techniques
